Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1/2} into roughly 1cm pieces. Peel the @carrot{1} and remove the top and bottom, halve it lengthways then slice into thin half moons. Quarter each @chestnut mushrooms{1}. Cut the @sweetheart cabbage{1/2} in half lengthways, remove its triangle root, then cut into ½cm wide slices. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1/2}(finely chopped) (stalks and all!). Drain and rinse the @butter beans{1/2} in a #colander{}.

Take the @unsalted butter{15%g} out of the fridge so it can come up to room temperature. Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Chop each @British honey mustard sausages{4} into five pieces. Put a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the sausage pieces. Cook, stirring occasionally, until they are nice and brown, ~{8-9%minutes}.

Add the onion and carrot to the pan with the sausages. Cook for ~{5%minutes}. Add the mushrooms, half the garlic, @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @black pepper{grind}. Stir together and cook until the mushrooms are browned, about ~{5%minutes} more.

Add the @white wine vinegar{1/2} to the pan and allow it to evaporate, ~{1-2%minutes}. Then add the @plain flour{12%g} and stir to distribute evenly. Cook for ~{2%minutes}. Pour in the @water{300}, along with the @beef stock pot{1/2}. Bring to the boil, making sure the stock pot has dissolved, then turn the heat to low and add the butter beans. Simmer for ~{10%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

Meanwhile, put the butter in a #bowl{} with half the parsley and the remaining garlic. Season with @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch} and mix together thoroughly.

> The best way to do this is to get stuck in and use your hands!

Slice the @ciabatta{1} in half (as if you are making a sandwich) and spread the garlic butter over each half. Place on a #baking tray{} and pop on the top shelf of the oven. Cook until slightly browned, ~{6-7%minutes}.

Add the sliced cabbage to the stew and stir it in. Cook until the cabbage is soft, ~{5-7%minutes}. When the garlic ciabatta is ready, remove from the oven and cut each piece into eight chunks. Stir the remaining parsley through the stew and serve in #bowls{} with the garlic croutons on top. Enjoy!